{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514185"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:19:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:19:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12289"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12289"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.04,0.16,0.6,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51988"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4811"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12289"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37292"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"9042"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7721"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14258"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14754"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51988","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51988"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of severe pain in his right eye. This is associated with lacrimation, photophobia, redness and decreased visual acuity. He has a medical history of type 1 diabetes and chronic urticaria, for which he has been taking prednisone for the last six months. He is myopic and wears contact lenses. He works as a farmer and enjoys swimming and hiking. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His vital signs are within normal limits. His visual acuity is 6/9 in the left eye and 6/24 in the right eye. Examination of the right eye reveals increased intraocular pressure, ciliary congestion, a dendritic-shaped epithelial defect, pus in the anterior chamber, ring abscesses and perineural infiltrates.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Episcleritis","Conjunctivitis","Corneal ulcer","Acanthamoeba keratitis","Acute angle-closure glaucoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eacanthamoeba keratitis\u003C/strong\u003E. Whilst herpes simplex virus keratitis, bacterial keratitis and fungal keratitis presents similarly, key features supporting the diagnosis of acanthamoeba keratitis include the presence of ring abscesses, dendritic-shaped epithelial defects (pseudodendrites), and perineural infiltrates on ocular examination. Additionally, the patient has significant risk factors for acanthamoeba keratitis, including contact lens wear and swimming. Acanthamoeba is commonly found in tap water, and using tap water to wet contact lenses is a frequent cause of this infection. Patients with acanthamoeba keratitis typically present with severe pain (often disproportionate to clinical findings), lacrimation, photophobia, redness, and decreased visual acuity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiscleritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with mild discomfort and localised redness of the eye. It does not cause decreased visual acuity, increased intraocular pressure, or the corneal findings described in this case. The severity of symptoms and the presence of ring abscesses and perineural infiltrates make episcleritis an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by redness, discharge, and mild discomfort. It does not typically cause severe pain, decreased visual acuity (apart from obscurity by the discharge), or corneal involvement. The presence of ring abscesses, perineural infiltrates, and a dendritic-shaped epithelial defect are not features of conjunctivitis, making this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECorneal ulcer\u003C/strong\u003E can cause eye pain, redness, and decreased visual acuity and are associated with contact lens use. However, the presence of ring abscesses and perineural infiltrates are not typical features of a standard corneal ulcer. While a corneal ulcer may be present in this case, it is likely secondary to a specific pathogen, namely Acanthamoeba, rather than being the primary diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute angle-closure glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E can present with similar symptoms and increased intraocular pressure. However, it is not associated with epithelial defects, hypopyon, or ring abscess formation. The presence of these findings makes acanthamoeba keratitis a more likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ring abscess and perineural infiltrates are characteristic features of acanthamoeba keratitis.","Contact lens wear and swimming are significant risk factors for acanthamoeba keratitis.","Acanthamoeba keratitis typically presents with severe pain, often disproportionate to clinical findings."],"references":["de Lacerda AG, Lira M. Acanthamoeba keratitis: a review of biology, pathophysiology and epidemiology. Ophthalmic Physiol Opt. 2021 Jan;41(1):116-135. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33119189/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37292"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12289"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18392"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18392"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5f2ea487-c87f-45d3-8372-15af2d6de391.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/5f2ea487-c87f-45d3-8372-15af2d6de391.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":567,"height":379}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37292","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37292"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-01T13:15:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-01T13:16:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4811"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51988"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":n